Currently, slice on an MKLDNN array requires to convert the array to the default layout before taking a slice. However, the MKLDNN library actually provides a view for MKLDNN memory. As such, by taking advantage of the MKLDNN view, we don't really need to convert data layout for slice. 
For details, please see the discussion here: https://github.com/intel/mkl-dnn/issues/306, https://github.com/intel/mkl-dnn/issues/69, https://github.com/intel/mkl-dnn/issues/290
@pengzhao-intel @TaoLv @azai91 @safrooze

When the jQuery object is constructed with jQuery 2.2.4:

```js
$el = $('body')
```

It carries the original string selector in the property `selector`:

```js
$el.selector === 'body'
```

When the jQuery object is constructed with jQuery 3.0.0 or 3.2.1, the original selector is not present:

```js
$el.selector === undefined
```
The old implementation of `jQuery.fn.find` set the `selector` property on the returned object:

```js
jQuery.fn.extend( {
	find: function( selector ) {
		var i,
			len = this.length,
			ret = [],
			self = this;

		if ( typeof selector !== "string" ) {
			return this.pushStack( jQuery( selector ).filter( function() {
				for ( i = 0; i < len; i++ ) {
					if ( jQuery.contains( self[ i ], this ) ) {
						return true;
					}
				}
			} ) );
		}

		for ( i = 0; i < len; i++ ) {
			jQuery.find( selector, self[ i ], ret );
		}

		// Needed because $( selector, context ) becomes $( context ).find( selector )
		ret = this.pushStack( len > 1 ? jQuery.unique( ret ) : ret );
		ret.selector = this.selector ? this.selector + " " + selector : selector;
		return ret;
	},
```

The new implementation doesn't need and doesn't set it any more:

```js
jQuery.fn.extend( {
	find: function( selector ) {
		var i, ret,
			len = this.length,
			self = this;

		if ( typeof selector !== "string" ) {
			return this.pushStack( jQuery( selector ).filter( function() {
				for ( i = 0; i < len; i++ ) {
					if ( jQuery.contains( self[ i ], this ) ) {
						return true;
					}
				}
			} ) );
		}

		ret = this.pushStack( [] );

		for ( i = 0; i < len; i++ ) {
			jQuery.find( selector, self[ i ], ret );
		}

		return len > 1 ? jQuery.uniqueSort( ret ) : ret;
	},
```

If some code written with jQuery 2.x depended on the `selector` property, upgrading to jQuery 3.x will break it. Concretely, this affects [Backbone.Marionette](https://github.com/marionettejs/backbone.marionette) 2.x, including the most recent 2.x release -  2.4.7. (The most recent Marionette 3.x release [fixed the problem](https://github.com/marionettejs/backbone.marionette/issues/2668) by storing the original property in their own object and not depending on this jQuery behaviour any more.) The implication of this is severe - re-re-rendering of a `Marionette.LayoutView` will throw an error and the view will remain empty:

```
Error: An "el" undefined must exist in DOM
    at constructor._ensureElement (http://localhost:8888/src/lib/marionette.js?:1238:17)
    at constructor.show (http://localhost:8888/src/lib/marionette.js?:1092:17)
    at BreadcrumbsPanelView.onRender (http://localhost:8888/src/controls/breadcrumbspanel/breadcrumbspanel.view.js?:86:29)
    at Object._triggerMethod (http://localhost:8888/src/lib/marionette.js?:688:25)
    at BreadcrumbsPanelView.triggerMethod (http://localhost:8888/src/lib/marionette.js?:1984:28)
    at BreadcrumbsPanelView.render (http://localhost:8888/src/lib/marionette.js?:2134:12)
    at BreadcrumbsPanelView.render (http://localhost:8888/src/lib/marionette.js?:3140:51)
    at executeBound (http://localhost:8888/src/lib/underscore.js?:734:67)
    at BreadcrumbsPanelView.<anonymous> (http://localhost:8888/src/lib/underscore.js?:747:14)
    at BreadcrumbsPanelView.render (http://localhost:8888/src/lib/underscore.js?:122:29)
```

There can be other applications depending on the existence of the `selector` property.

* Do you agree, that jQuery Migrate plugin should help applications, which depend on the `selector` property, to run, detect the issue and fix it, as long as they use jQuery Migrate plugin?
* Would you accept a PR restoring the property getter with a warning?

